@startuml RateLimiting

title High-Level Design: Rate Limiting

skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam componentStyle rectangle

actor "Client" as client

rectangle "API Gateway /\nRate Limiter Middleware" as rl #DDEEFF {
    component [Rate Limit Filter] as filter
    component [Algorithm Engine\n(Token Bucket /\nLeaky Bucket /\nSliding Window)] as engine
}

component "Redis\n(Counter Store)" as redis #FFF2CC
component "Application\nService" as app #D5E8D4

client --> filter : HTTP Request

filter --> engine  : Check limit for\nclient key (IP / userId / API key)
engine --> redis   : GET / INCR counter
redis  --> engine  : Current count + TTL

engine --> filter  : ALLOW / DENY

filter --> client  : 429 Too Many Requests\n(Retry-After header)
filter --> app     : Allowed → forward request
app    --> client  : 200 OK + response

note right of engine
  **Algorithms Compared:**

  Token Bucket
  • Tokens added at fixed rate
  • Burst traffic allowed up to bucket size
  • Smooth & flexible

  Leaky Bucket
  • Requests queued, drained at fixed rate
  • No burst — strictly smooth output

  Fixed Window Counter
  • Count resets every window (e.g. 1 min)
  • Edge case: burst at window boundary

  Sliding Window Log
  • Stores timestamp of each request
  • Accurate, but memory heavy

  Sliding Window Counter
  • Hybrid: smooth + efficient
  • Weighted average of current & prev window
end note

note right of redis
  **Key schema:**
  rate_limit:{userId}:{windowTs} = count
  EXPIRE set to window duration (TTL)

  Distributed rate limiting uses
  Redis atomic INCR + EXPIRE commands
  or Lua scripts for atomicity.
end note

note bottom of client
  **Response Headers:**
  X-RateLimit-Limit: 100
  X-RateLimit-Remaining: 42
  X-RateLimit-Reset: 1720000000
  Retry-After: 30
end note

@enduml

